Abstract

This paper introduces AET (Assured Execution Time) , 
a novel paradigm for AI inference that guarantees 
physically deterministic execution timing independent
of model complexity, system state, or hardware variability. 
Unlike traditional WCET (Worst-Case Execution Time) analysis, 
which seeks to bound execution time, AET eliminates
timing variability at the architectural level.

We present the ST-T1024 standard as the first implementation of AET, 
achieving 680 ns latency and 3.7 µJ per query on commodity hardware.
We draw a historical parallel to RTX-2 (1990s), the only known real-time operating system 
that achieved thread-count-independent timing for MUTEX-blocked transitions —
a precedent that validates the AET approach.

