1. Introduction

1.1 The Problem: Stochastic AI, Stochastic Timing

Current AI inference is fundamentally non-deterministic:

· Execution time varies with model size, input length, cache state, and hardware load.
· Latency is expressed as averages, percentiles, or worst-case bounds — never as guaranteed constants.
· Safety certification (IEC 61508, ISO 26262) requires deterministic timing — a requirement stochastic AI cannot meet.

This is not a bug. It is a structural property of stochastic transformers running on general-purpose hardware.

1.2 The Solution: AET (Assured Execution Time)

AET replaces probabilistic timing with physical determinism:

· Execution time is fixed — known before compilation.
· Execution time is independent — of model size, input, and system state.
· Execution time is verifiable — through cycle-accurate simulation and hardware counters.

ST-T1024 implements AET through three architectural pillars:

1. Ternary Logic (1.58-bit) — eliminates floating-point uncertainty.
2. FSM Orchestration — cycle-accurate scheduling with WCET ≤ 800 ns.
3. Power Gating — tiles activate in <5 ns and return to 0V instantly.

