2. The Precedent: RTX-2 (1990s)

2.1 What RTX-2 Achieved

RTX (Real-Time eXtensions) for Windows NT, developed by VenturCom (later IntervalZero), extended a general-purpose OS into a hard real-time system.

 RTX-1 RTX-2
Timing dependency Dependent on number of threads Independent of thread count
Critical metric MUTEX-blocked thread transition time MUTEX-blocked thread transition time — constant
Method Priority-based scheduling Undisclosed (proprietary)
Significance Bounded real-time response Truly deterministic real-time response

RTX-2 proved that:

· Thread-count-independent timing is achievable on commercial hardware.
· This requires architectural change, not just scheduler optimization.
· The result can be verified — even if the method remains proprietary.

2.2 The Silence on Method

Critically, RTX-2 did not publish how it achieved thread-count independence.

This created:

· Vendor lock-in — only the vendor could implement it.
· Skepticism — some questioned the verifiability of the claim.
· Dependency — any adopter had to license the secret.

2.3 The Parallel to AET

RTX-2 ST-T1024 / AET
Thread-count-independent timing Model-complexity-independent timing
MUTEX-blocked transitions — constant time Inference execution — constant time
Proprietary method Open standard (Apache-2.0)
Result published, method hidden Method fully disclosed
Single vendor control Any nation/engineer can implement

RTX-2 is the only known historical precedent for AET. It proves the concept is viable. ST-T1024 completes the vision by making it open, verifiable, and sovereign.

