3. AET in ST-T1024: Architectural Implementation

3.1 Deterministic Foundations

ST-T1024 achieves AET through a hardware-first approach:

Component Function AET Contribution
Ternary Logic 1.58-bit (-1, 0, +1) Eliminates floating-point timing variability
FSM Scheduler Cycle-accurate task switching Guarantees WCET ≤ 800 ns
Domain Tiling N independent, isolated tiles Prevents cross-tile interference
Power Gating <5 ns activation, 0V idle Eliminates thermal/throttling variability
75% ROM / 25% SRAM Immutable constants + sovereign updates Removes loading-time variability

3.2 The AET Guarantee

For any query, on any tile, under any system state:

t_execution = 680 ns ± 0 ns (deterministic)
E_query = 3.7 µJ (fixed)
No variance. No percentiles. No worst-case bounds — only exact, physically assured time.

3.3 Verification

AET is verifiable through:

1. Cycle-accurate emulation — improved_st_t1024_v2.1.py
2. Hardware counters — on RISC-V implementation
3. Formal verification — FSM model-checking (TLA+, SPIN)
4. Benchmark reproducibility — simulation = benchmarking (no statistical variance)

